t of a Man” -- tPart Five: John Ashbery: “Time Is an Emulsion” -- tPart Six: Charles Bernstein: “Of Time and the Line” -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores the changing perception of time and space in avant-garde, modernist, and contemporary poetry. The author characterizes the works of modern Russian, French, and Anglo-American poets based on their attitudes towards reality, time, space, and history revealed in their poetics. The author compares the work of major Russian innovative poets Osip Mandelstam, Velimir Khlebnikov, Vladimir Mayakovsky, and Joseph Brodsky with that of W. B. Yeats, T. S. Eliot, Ezra Pound, and, in spite of the postmodernist “estrangement” of reality, the author proves that similar traces can be found in the work of contemporary American poets John Ashbery and Charles Bernstein. Both affinities and drastic differences are revealed in the poets’ attitudes towards time-space, reality, and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aComparative literaturexEnglish and Russian. 0aComparative literaturexRussian and English. 0aEnglish poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHistory in literature. 0aModernism (Literature)zEnglandxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zEngland. 0aModernism (Literature)zSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zSoviet Union. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature)zUnited States. 0aRussian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpace and time in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978161811627740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618116277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.c